# No Exposed Secrets

Never hardcode secrets, API keys, passwords, tokens, or other sensitive credentials in the codebase. Always use environment variables so that secrets can be configured per environment and remain out of version control.

## Guidelines

- Use environment variables for all secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens, private keys, database credentials, etc.)
- Store sample/placeholder values only in `.env.example` or similar template files, never in committed `.env`
- Never commit `.env` files that contain real secrets
- Add `.env` and `.env.local` to `.gitignore`

## Examples

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
const API_KEY = 'sk-1234567890abcdef';
const DB_PASSWORD = 'mySecretPassword123';

// ✅ GOOD
const API_KEY = import.meta.env.VITE_API_KEY ?? process.env.API_KEY;
const DB_PASSWORD = process.env.DB_PASSWORD;
```

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
fetch('/api/data', {
  headers: { 'Authorization': 'Bearer abc123token' }
});

// ✅ GOOD
fetch('/api/data', {
  headers: { 'Authorization': `Bearer ${process.env.API_TOKEN}` }
});
```
